00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:22,000
You're a fine armful now, Mary, with those

3
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:24,000
20 pounds you gained.

4
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:25,000
I've gotten too fat, you mean, dear, I

5
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:26,000
really ought to reduce.

6
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:28,000
Ah, none of that, my lady, you're just right.

7
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:32,000
We'll have no talk or reducing.

8
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:33,000
Is that why you ate so little breakfast?

9
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:35,000
So little?

10
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:36,000
I thought I ate a lot.

11
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:37,000
You didn't--

12
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:38,000
not as much as I'd like to see anyhow.

13
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:41,000
You expect everyone to eat the enormous breakfast you do?

14
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:45,000
No one else in the world could without dying of indigestion.

15
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:49,000
I hope I'm not as big a glutton as that sounds, but

16
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:51,000
thank god I've kept my appetite.

17
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:56,000
I have the digestion of a young man of 20, if I am 65.

18
00:00:56,000 --> 00:00:58,000
You surely have, James.

19
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:02,000
No one could deny that.

20
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:04,000
Why do the boys stay in the dining room, I wonder.

21
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:07,000
Kathleen must be waiting to clear the table

22
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:09,000
It's a secret confab they don't want

23
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:11,000
me to hear, I suppose.

24
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:14,000
I'll bet they're cooking up some new scheme to

25
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:17,000
touch the old man.

26
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:22,000
There's nothing like the first after breakfast cigar, if it's

27
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:23,000
a good one.

28
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:27,000
And this new lot have the right, mellow flavor.

29
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:28,000
They were great bargain too.

30
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:31,000
Got them dead cheap.

31
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:33,000
McGuire put me on to them.

32
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:35,000
I hope he didn't put you on to a new piece of property at the

33
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:37,000
same time, his real estate bargains

34
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:39,000
don't work out so well.

35
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:41,000
I wouldn't say that, Mary.

36
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:43,000
After all, he was the one who advised me to buy that place

37
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:45,000
on Chestnut Street and I made a quick turnover on it for a

38
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:46,000
fine profit.

39
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:51,000
Yes, I know The famous one stroke of good luck.

40
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:54,000
Oh, never mind, James.

41
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:56,000
I know it's a waste of breath trying to convince you you're

42
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:58,000
not a cunning real estate speculator.

43
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:02,000
I've no s such idea, but land is land.

44
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:03,000
That is safer than the stocks and bonds of

45
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:05,000
your Wall Street swindlers.

46
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:06,000
No, no.

47
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:10,000
Let's not argue about business this early in the morning.

48
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:13,000
James, it's Edmund you ought to scold

49
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:14,000
for not eating enough.

50
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:16,000
He hardly touched anything except coffee.

51
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:19,000
He needs to eat to keep up his strength.

52
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:21,000
I keep telling him that.

53
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:25,000
He says he simply has no appetite.

54
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:28,000
Of course, there's nothing takes away your appetite like

55
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:29,000
a bad summer cold.

56
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:29,000
Yes.

57
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:31,000
It's only natural, so don't let yourself get worried.

58
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:32,000
Oh, I'm not.

59
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:34,000
I know he'll be all right in a few days if he

60
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:36,000
takes care of himself.

61
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:39,000
But it does seem a shame he should have to

62
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:40,000
be sick right now.

63
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:43,000
Yes, it is bad luck, but you mustn't let it upset you.

64
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:45,000
Remember, you got to take care of yourself too.

65
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:45,000
Upset.

66
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:48,000
There's nothing to be upset about.

67
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:50,000
What makes you think I'm upset?

68
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:52,000
Nothing.

69
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:53,000
Except, you've seemed a bit high strung

70
00:02:53,000 --> 00:02:55,000
these past few days.

71
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:57,000
I have?

72
00:02:57,000 --> 00:02:58,000
Nonsense dear, it's your imagination.

73
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:01,000


74
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:04,000
But you really must not watch me all the time, James.

75
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:05,000
I mean, it makes me subconscious.

76
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:07,000
Now, now, Mary.

77
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:10,000
That's your imagination.

78
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:13,000
If I've watched you it was to admire how fat and

79
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:16,000
beautiful you look.

80
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:20,000
I can't tell you, darling, the deep happiness it gives me to

81
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:24,000
see you the way you've been since you've come back to us,

82
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:25,000
your dear old self again.

83
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:29,000


84
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:31,000
So keep up the good work, Mary.

85
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:32,000
I will, dear.

86
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:42,000


87
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:43,000
Thanks heavens, the fogs.

88
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:47,000


89
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:49,000
I do feel out of sorts this morning.

90
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:52,000
I wasn't able to get much sleep with that awful foghorn

91
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:54,000
going all night long.

92
00:03:54,000 --> 00:03:56,000
Yeah it's like having a sick whale in the backyard.

93
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:57,000
It kept me awake too.

94
00:03:57,000 --> 00:03:58,000
Did it?

95
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:01,000
You had a strange way of showing your restlessness.

96
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:03,000
You were snoring so hard, I couldn't tell

97
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:05,000
which was the foghorn.

98
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:08,000
10 foghorns couldn't disturb you.

99
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:10,000
You haven't a nerve in you,

100
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:11,000
you never have. Nonsense.

101
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:14,000
You always exaggerate about my snoring.

102
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:15,000
I couldn't.

103
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:17,000
If you could only hear yourself once.

104
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:20,000


105
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:22,000
What's the joke, I wonder?

106
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:23,000
It's on me.

107
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:24,000
I'll bet that much.

108
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:25,000
It's always on the old man.

109
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:28,000
Yes, it's terrible the way we all pick on you.

110
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:30,000
You're so abused.

111
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:32,000
No matter what the joke is, it's a relief

112
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:34,000
to hear Edmund laugh.

113
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:36,000
He's been so down in the mouth lately.

114
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:37,000
It's some joke of Jamie's, I'll wager.

115
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:40,000
He's forever making sneering fun of somebody that one.

116
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:41,000
Don't start in on poor Jamie.

117
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:42,000
He'll turn out all right in the end.

118
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:44,000
You wait and see.

119
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:45,000
He'd better start soon.

120
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:47,000
He's nearly 34.

121
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:47,000
Heavens, are they going to stay in the

122
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:48,000
dining room all day?

123
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:49,000
Jamie?

124
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:50,000
Edmund?

125
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:51,000
Come in the living room.

126
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:53,000
Give Cathleen a chance to clear the table.

127
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:54,000
Coming, Mama.

128
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:56,000
You'd find excuses for him no matter what he did.

129
00:04:56,000 --> 00:05:01,000


130
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:04,000
I've been teasing your father about his snoring.

131
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:05,000
I'll leave it to the boys, James.

132
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:08,000
They must have heard you.

133
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:08,000
Not you, Jamie.

134
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:11,000
I could hear you down the hall almost as bad as your father.

135
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:12,000
You're like him.

136
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:15,000
As soon as your head touches the pillow, you're off and 10

137
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:17,000
foghorns couldn't wake you.

138
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:19,000
Why are you staring, Jamie?

139
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:21,000
Is my hair coming down?

140
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:23,000
It's hard for me to do it up properly now my eyes are

141
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:25,000
getting so bad and I never can find my glasses.

142
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:27,000
Your hair's all right, Mama.

143
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:29,000
I was only thinking how well you look.

144
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:31,000
Yeah, that's just what I was telling her, Jamie.

145
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:34,000
Yes, you certainly look grand, Mama.

146
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:37,000
And I'll back you up about Papa's snoring.

147
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:38,000
Gosh, what a racket.

148
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:40,000
I heard him too.

149
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:42,000
"The moor, I know his trumpet."

150
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:43,000
Well, if it takes my snoring to make you remember

151
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:45,000
Shakespeare, instead of the dope sheet on the ponies, I

152
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:47,000
hope I'll keep on with it.

153
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:48,000
James, you mustn't be so touchy.

154
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:49,000
For pete's sake, Papa.

155
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:50,000
The first thing after breakfast?

156
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:51,000
Give it a rest.

157
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:52,000
Your father wasn't finding fault with you.

158
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:54,000
You don't have to always take Jamie's part.

159
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:56,000
You'd think you were the one 10 years older.

160
00:05:56,000 --> 00:05:57,000
What's all the fuss about?

161
00:05:57,000 --> 00:05:57,000
Let's forget it.

162
00:05:57,000 --> 00:05:58,000
Yeah, forget.

163
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Forget everything and face nothing.

164
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:02,000
It's a convenient philosophy if you've got no ambition in

165
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:03,000
life except to--

166
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:04,000
Do be quiet.

167
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:05,000
You must have gotten out of the wrong side of

168
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:07,000
the bed this morning.

169
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:10,000
What were you two grinning about like Cheshire cats when

170
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:10,000
you came in?

171
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:11,000
What was the joke?

172
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:13,000
Yeah, let us in on it, lads.

173
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:15,000
I was telling your mother, I know damn well it will be on

174
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:16,000
me, but never mind I'm used to it.

175
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:18,000
Well, don't look at me.

176
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:21,000
This is the kid's story.

177
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:26,000
Well, I meant to tell you last night and forgot it.

178
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:29,000
Yesterday, when I went out for a walk, I

179
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:30,000
dropped in at the inn.

180
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:31,000
You shouldn't drink now, Edmund.

181
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:33,000
And who do you think I met there-- with a

182
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:34,000
beautiful bun on--

183
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:37,000
but Shaughnessy, the tenant on that farm of yours.

184
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:38,000
That dreadful man.

185
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:39,000
But he is funny.

186
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:42,000
Yeah, well he's not funny when you're his landlord.

187
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:43,000
He's a wily, Shanty Mick that one.

188
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:46,000
He could hide behind a corkscrew.

189
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:48,000
What's he complaining about now, Edmund?

190
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:49,000
For I'm damn sure he's complaining.

191
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:50,000
I suppose he wants his rent lowered.

192
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:51,000
No.

193
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:52,000
He didn't beef about anything.

194
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:55,000
He was so pleased with life he even bought a drink and that's

195
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:56,000
practically unheard of.

196
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:59,000
No, he was delighted because he'd had a fight with your

197
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:02,000
friend, Harker-- the standard oil millionaire--

198
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:03,000
and won a glorious victory.

199
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:06,000
Yeah, I'll bet the next time you see Harker at the club and

200
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:09,000
give him the old, respectful bow, he won't see you.

201
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:11,000
Harker will think you're no gentleman for harboring a

202
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:14,000
tenant who isn't humble in the presence of a King of--

203
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:15,000
Never mind the socialist gabble.

204
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:15,000
I don't care to listen to it--

205
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:19,000
Go on with your story, Edmund.

206
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:21,000
You remember, Papa, the ice pond on Harker's estate is

207
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:22,000
right next to the farm.

208
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:24,000
You remember Shaughnessy keeps pigs?

209
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:28,000
Well it seems there's a break in the fence and the pigs have

210
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:31,000
been bathing in the millionaire's ice pond.

211
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:33,000
And Harker's foreman told him he was sure Shaughnessy had

212
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:36,000
broken the fence on purpose to give his pigs a free wallow.

213
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:36,000
Good heavens.

214
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:38,000
I'm sure he did, too, the dirty scallywag.

215
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:39,000
It's like him.

216
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:42,000
So, Harker comes in person to rebuke Shaughnessy.

217
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:45,000
Well, what happened?

218
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:47,000
Shaughnessy got a few drinks under his belt.

219
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:49,000
He's waiting at the gait to welcome him.

220
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:51,000
He didn't give Harker a chance to open his mouth.

221
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:54,000
Shaughnessy accused Harker of making his forman break down

222
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:56,000
the fence to entice the pigs into the ice pond in order to

223
00:07:56,000 --> 00:07:58,000
destroy them.

224
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:01,000
The poor pigs, Shaughnessy yelled, have got

225
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:02,000
their deaths of cold.

226
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:05,000
Many of them are dying of pneumonia and several others

227
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:07,000
have taken down with cholera from drinking

228
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:08,000
the poisoned water.

229
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:11,000
He told Harker he was hiring a lawyer to sue him for damages.

230
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:13,000
And he wound up by saying he be damned if he'd stand for a

231
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:16,000
standard oil thief trespassing, so would Harker

232
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:18,000
kindly remove his dirty feet from the premises before he

233
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:19,000
sicked the dogs on him.

234
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:20,000
And Harker did.

235
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:24,000


236
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:26,000
What a terrible tongue that man has.

237
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:27,000
That damned old scoundrel.

238
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:29,000
By God, you can't beat him.

239
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:35,000


240
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:37,000
The dirty blackguard, he'll get me into more serious

241
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:38,000
trouble yet.

242
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:40,000
I hope you told him I'd be mad as hell.

243
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:42,000
I told him you'd be tickled to death over

244
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:43,000
the great Irish victory.

245
00:08:43,000 --> 00:08:44,000
And so you are, stop faking, Papa.

246
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:45,000
Well, I'm not tickled to death.

247
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:46,000
Oh, you are too, James, you're simply delighted.

248
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:48,000
No Mary, a joke is a joke.

249
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:49,000
What are you laughing at?

250
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:50,000
There's nothing funny.

251
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:52,000
A fine son you are to help that blackguard get

252
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:52,000
me into a law suit.

253
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:55,000
And you're worse than he is encouraging him.

254
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:57,000
I suppose you regret you weren't there to prompt

255
00:08:57,000 --> 00:08:58,000
Shaughnessy with a few nastier insults.

256
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:01,000
You've got a fine talent for that if nothing else.

257
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:02,000
James, there's no reason to scold Jamie.

258
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:03,000
For God's sake, Papa.

259
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:05,000
If you're going to start that stuff again, I'll beat it.

260
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:15,000


261
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:18,000
I left my book upstairs anyway.

262
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:19,000
God, Papa, I should think you'd get

263
00:09:19,000 --> 00:09:22,000
sick of hearing yourself.

264
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:24,000
You mustn't mind Edmund, James.

265
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:26,000
Remember he isn't well.

266
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:28,000
A summer cold makes anyone irritable.

267
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:31,000
It's not just a cold he's got.

268
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:33,000
The kid is damn sick.

269
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:34,000
Why do you say that?

270
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:35,000
It is just a cold.

271
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:36,000
Anyone can tell that.

272
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:37,000
Always imagine things.

273
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:40,000
All Jamie meant was that Edmund may have a touch of

274
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:42,000
something else that makes his cold a little worse.

275
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:45,000


276
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:46,000
Sure, Mama.

277
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:48,000
That's all I meant.

278
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:50,000
Dr. Hardy thinks it might be a touch of malarial fever he

279
00:09:50,000 --> 00:09:52,000
caught when he was in the tropics.

280
00:09:52,000 --> 00:09:53,000
If so, quinine will soon cure it.

281
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:55,000
Dr. Hardy, I wouldn't believe a thing he said if he swore on

282
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:57,000
a stack of bibles.

283
00:09:57,000 --> 00:09:58,000
I know what doctors are.

284
00:09:58,000 --> 00:09:59,000
They're all alike.

285
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:00,000
Anything, they don't care what, to keep

286
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:02,000
you coming to them.

287
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:03,000
What?

288
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:04,000
What is it?

289
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:06,000
What are you looking at?

290
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:07,000
Is my hair--

291
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:10,000
There's nothing wrong with your hair.

292
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:14,000
The fatter and healthier you get, the vainer you become.

293
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:16,000
You'll soon be spending half the day primping in front of

294
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:16,000
the mirror.

295
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:18,000
I really should have new glasses.

296
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:22,000
My eyes are so bad now.

297
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:25,000
Your eyes are beautiful and well you know it.

298
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:31,000
Oh James, you're being so silly right in front of Jamie.

299
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:34,000
But I did truly have beautiful hair once, didn't I James?

300
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:36,000
The most beautiful in the world.

301
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:40,000
It was a rare shade of reddish brown and so long it came down

302
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:41,000
below my knees.

303
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:42,000
You ought to remember it too, Jamie.

304
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:45,000
It wasn't until after Edmund was born that I had

305
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:46,000
a single grey hair.

306
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:48,000
Then it began to turn white.

307
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:51,000
And that made it prettier than ever.

308
00:10:51,000 --> 00:10:53,000
Would you listen to your father, Jamie?

309
00:10:53,000 --> 00:10:57,000
After 35 years of marriage, he isn't a great actor for

310
00:10:57,000 --> 00:10:58,000
nothing, is he?

311
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:00,000
What's come over you, James?

312
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:04,000
Are you pouring coals of fire on my head for teasing you

313
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:05,000
about snoring?

314
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:07,000
Well, then I take it all back.

315
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:09,000
It must have been only the foghorn I heard.

316
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:13,000


317
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:15,000
But I can't stay with you any longer, even to here

318
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:16,000
compliments.

319
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:17,000
I must see the cook about dinner

320
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:20,000
and the day's marketing.

321
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:22,000
That Bridget is so lazy and so sly.

322
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:25,000
She begins telling me about her relatives so I can't get a

323
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:28,000
word in edgeways and scold her.

324
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:33,000
Well, I might as well get it over with.

325
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:36,000
You mustn't make Edmund work on the grounds with you,

326
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:37,000
James, remember?

327
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:40,000
Not that he isn't strong enough, but he'd perspire.

328
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:41,000
He might catch more cold.

329
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:53,000


330
00:11:53,000 --> 00:11:55,000
You're a fine lunkhead.

331
00:11:55,000 --> 00:11:57,000
Haven't you any sense?

332
00:11:57,000 --> 00:11:59,000
The one thing to avoid is saying anything that'll get

333
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:00,000
her more upset--

334
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:03,000
Oh, all right.

335
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:05,000
Have it your way.

336
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:07,000
But I think it's the wrong idea to let her go on kidding

337
00:12:07,000 --> 00:12:09,000
herself with this summer cold talk.

338
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:11,000
She knows better than that.

339
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:11,000
Knows?

340
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:12,000
Nobody knows yet.

341
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:14,000
Well I do.

342
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:17,000
I was with Edmund when he saw Doc Hardy on Monday.

343
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:19,000
I heard him pull that touch of malaria stuff.

344
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:21,000
He was stalling.

345
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:22,000
That isn't what he thinks anymore.

346
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:24,000
You know it as well as I do.

347
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:25,000
You talked to him yesterday when you went

348
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:26,000
uptown, didn't you?

349
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:28,000
He couldn't say anything for sure yet.

350
00:12:28,000 --> 00:12:31,000
He's to call me today before Edmund goes to him.

351
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:37,000
He thinks it's consumption, doesn't he Papa?

352
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:40,000
He said it might be.

353
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:42,000
Poor kid.

354
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:43,000
God damn it.

355
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:45,000
It might never have happened if you'd sent him to a real

356
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:46,000
doctor when he first got sick.

357
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:48,000
What's the matter what Hardy?

358
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:49,000
Huh?

359
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:50,000
He's always been our doctor up here.

360
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:53,000
Everything's the matter with him.

361
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:55,000
Even in this hick burg he's rated third class.

362
00:12:55,000 --> 00:12:56,000
He's a cheap old quack.

363
00:12:56,000 --> 00:12:57,000
That's right, run him down.

364
00:12:57,000 --> 00:12:58,000
Run everyone down.

365
00:12:58,000 --> 00:12:59,000
Everybody's a fake to you.

366
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:00,000
Hardy only charges $1.

367
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:02,000
That's what makes you think he such a fine doctor.

368
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:03,000
That's enough.

369
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:04,000
You're not drunk now.

370
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:06,000
There's no excuse.

371
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:09,000
If you mean I can't afford one of those fine, society doctors

372
00:13:09,000 --> 00:13:10,000
that prey on the rich summer people--

373
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:12,000
Can't afford?

374
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:13,000
you're one of the biggest property owners around here.

375
00:13:13,000 --> 00:13:15,000
That doesn't mean I'm rich.

376
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:15,000
It's all mortgages.

377
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:17,000
Yeah, because you keep on buying instead

378
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:18,000
of paying off mortgages.

379
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:21,000
If Edmund was a lousy acre of land you wanted, the sky would

380
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:21,000
be the limit.

381
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:22,000
That's a lie.

382
00:13:22,000 --> 00:13:24,000
And your sneers against doctor Hardy are lies.

383
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:26,000
All right.

384
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:27,000
I'm a fool to argue.

385
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:31,000


386
00:13:31,000 --> 00:13:33,000
You can't change the leopard's spots.

387
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:34,000
No you can't.

388
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:36,000
You've taught me that lesson only too well.

389
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:38,000
I've lost all hope you'll ever change yours.

390
00:13:38,000 --> 00:13:40,000
You dare tell me what I can afford.

391
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:42,000
You've never known the value of a dollar

392
00:13:42,000 --> 00:13:42,000
and never will you.

393
00:13:42,000 --> 00:13:44,000
You've never saved a dollar in your life.

394
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:45,000
At the end of each season you're penniless.

395
00:13:45,000 --> 00:13:47,000
You've thrown your salary away every week

396
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:48,000
on whores and whiskey--

397
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:48,000
My salary.

398
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:48,000
Christ.

399
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:50,000
Yeah, well it's more than you're worth and you wouldn't

400
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:51,000
get that if it wasn't for me.

401
00:13:51,000 --> 00:13:53,000
If you were'nt my son, there isn't a manager in the

402
00:13:53,000 --> 00:13:55,000
business who'd give you a part.

403
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:56,000
Your reputation stinks so.

404
00:13:56,000 --> 00:13:57,000
I never wanted to be an actor.

405
00:13:57,000 --> 00:13:59,000
You forced me on the stage.

406
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:00,000
Forced you?

407
00:14:00,000 --> 00:14:02,000
You never wanted to do anything except loaf in

408
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:04,000
barrooms. You'd have been content to sit back like a

409
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:07,000
lazy lunk and sponge off me for the rest of your life.

410
00:14:07,000 --> 00:14:10,000
And after all the money I've wasted on your education, all

411
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:12,000
you did was get fired and disgraced from every college

412
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:12,000
you ever went to--

413
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:12,000
Oh for God's sake.

414
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:13,000
Don't drag up that ancient history.

415
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:15,000
Yeah, well it's not ancient history when you have to come

416
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:16,000
home every summer and live on me.

417
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:19,000
I earn my board and lodging working on the grounds.

418
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:20,000
Saves you hiring a man.

419
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:22,000
You have to be driven to do even that much.

420
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:29,000


421
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:31,000
I wouldn't give a damn if you displayed

422
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:34,000
the slightest gratitude.

423
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:36,000
But the only thanks is to have you sneer at me for a dirty

424
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:40,000
miser, sneer at my profession, sneer at every damn thing in

425
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:42,000
the world except yourself.

426
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:45,000
That's not true, Papa.

427
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:48,000
You can't hear me talking to myself that's all.

428
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:51,000
If you'd get ambition in your head instead of folly, you're

429
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:52,000
young yet, you could still make your mark.

430
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:54,000
You had a talent to become a fine actor.

431
00:14:54,000 --> 00:14:55,000
You have it still.

432
00:14:55,000 --> 00:14:57,000
You're my son.

433
00:14:57,000 --> 00:14:59,000
Let's forget about me.

434
00:14:59,000 --> 00:15:03,000
I'm not interested in the subject and neither are you.

435
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:06,000
What started us on this?

436
00:15:06,000 --> 00:15:10,000
Oh, Doc Hardy.

437
00:15:10,000 --> 00:15:12,000
Well, when is he going to call you up about Edmund?

438
00:15:12,000 --> 00:15:13,000
Around lunchtime.

439
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:15,000


440
00:15:15,000 --> 00:15:17,000
I couldn't have sent Edmund to a better doctor.

441
00:15:17,000 --> 00:15:19,000
Hardy's treated him whenever he was sick up here, ever

442
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:21,000
since he was knee high.

443
00:15:21,000 --> 00:15:23,000
And what could the finest specialists in America do for

444
00:15:23,000 --> 00:15:26,000
Edmund, after he's deliberately ruined his health

445
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:27,000
by the mad life he's led ever since he

446
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:29,000
was fired from college?

447
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:31,000
He's always been a bundle of nerves like his mother.

448
00:15:31,000 --> 00:15:34,000
And I warned him for years his body wouldn't stand it.

449
00:15:34,000 --> 00:15:35,000
He wouldn't heed me.

450
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:37,000
Now it's too late.

451
00:15:37,000 --> 00:15:40,000
What do you mean, too late?

452
00:15:40,000 --> 00:15:40,000
You talk as if you thought he was--

453
00:15:40,000 --> 00:15:43,000
Don't be a damn fool.

454
00:15:43,000 --> 00:15:45,000
I meant nothing but what's plain to everyone.

455
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:46,000
His health is broken down and he may be an

456
00:15:46,000 --> 00:15:47,000
invalid for some time.

457
00:15:47,000 --> 00:15:50,000
I know it's an Irish peasant idea that

458
00:15:50,000 --> 00:15:52,000
consumption is fatal.

459
00:15:52,000 --> 00:15:55,000
It probably is when you live in a hovel on a bog.

460
00:15:55,000 --> 00:15:56,000
But over here, with modern treatment there's no--

461
00:15:56,000 --> 00:15:58,000
Keep your dirty tongue off Ireland with your sneers about

462
00:15:58,000 --> 00:16:00,000
peasants and bogs and hovels.

463
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:03,000
And the less you say about Edmund's sickness, the better

464
00:16:03,000 --> 00:16:04,000
for your conscience.

465
00:16:04,000 --> 00:16:06,000
You're more responsible than anyone.

466
00:16:06,000 --> 00:16:07,000
That's a lie, Papa.

467
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:08,000
I won't stand for that.

468
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:09,000
It's the truth.

469
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:11,000
You've been the worst influence for him, pumping him

470
00:16:11,000 --> 00:16:14,000
full of what you consider worldly wisdom.

471
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:16,000
When he was too young to see that your mind was so poisoned

472
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:18,000
by your own failure in life, you wanted to believe every

473
00:16:18,000 --> 00:16:21,000
man was a knave with his soul for sale and every woman who

474
00:16:21,000 --> 00:16:23,000
wasn't a whore was a fool.

475
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:26,000
All right, I did put Edmund wise to things.

476
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:29,000
But not until I'd seen he'd started to raise hell and knew

477
00:16:29,000 --> 00:16:30,000
he'd laugh at me if I used that good advice

478
00:16:30,000 --> 00:16:33,000
older brother stuff.

479
00:16:33,000 --> 00:16:35,000
Besides, it's damned rot.

480
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:38,000
He's as stubborn as hell inside and what he does is

481
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:40,000
what he wants to do and to hell with anybody else.

482
00:16:40,000 --> 00:16:42,000
What had I to do with the crazy stunts he's pulled in

483
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:43,000
the last few years--

484
00:16:43,000 --> 00:16:45,000
working his way all over the map as a sailor

485
00:16:45,000 --> 00:16:46,000
and all that stuff?

486
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:50,000
I thought it was a damned fool idea and I told him so.

487
00:16:50,000 --> 00:16:53,000
You can't imagine me getting fun being on a beach in South

488
00:16:53,000 --> 00:16:56,000
America or living in a filthy dive drinking rotgut--

489
00:16:56,000 --> 00:16:58,000
Well, at least he's had the guts to go off on his own

490
00:16:58,000 --> 00:17:00,000
where he couldn't come whining to me the minute he was broke.

491
00:17:00,000 --> 00:17:02,000
He's always come home broke, finally, hasn't he?

492
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:04,000
And what's his going away got him?

493
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:05,000
Look at him now.

494
00:17:05,000 --> 00:17:10,000


495
00:17:10,000 --> 00:17:15,000
Oh, Christ. That's a lousy thing to say.

496
00:17:15,000 --> 00:17:17,000
That's not what I meant.

497
00:17:17,000 --> 00:17:18,000
He's been doing well on that newspaper.

498
00:17:18,000 --> 00:17:21,000


499
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:24,000
A hick town rag.

500
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:26,000
Whatever bull they hand you, they tell me he's

501
00:17:26,000 --> 00:17:27,000
a pretty bum reporter.

502
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:28,000
If he weren't your son--

503
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:29,000
Well, at least he's made a start.

504
00:17:29,000 --> 00:17:32,000
You used to talk about wanting to be a newspaperman, but you

505
00:17:32,000 --> 00:17:33,000
were never willing to start at the bottom--

506
00:17:33,000 --> 00:17:34,000
Oh for Christ's sake.

507
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:35,000
Can't you lay off me?

508
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:42,000


509
00:17:42,000 --> 00:17:44,000
It's damnable luck Edmund should get sick right now.

510
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:46,000
It couldn't come at a worse time for

511
00:17:46,000 --> 00:17:49,000
him or for your mother.

512
00:17:49,000 --> 00:17:51,000
It's damnable she should have this to upset her just when

513
00:17:51,000 --> 00:17:55,000
she needs peace and freedom from worry.

514
00:17:55,000 --> 00:17:58,000
She had been so well in the two months

515
00:17:58,000 --> 00:18:00,000
since she's been home.

516
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:03,000
It's been heaven to me.

517
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:05,000
This home has seemed like a home again.

518
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:08,000


519
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:09,000
But I needn't tell you, Jamie.

520
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:15,000


521
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:17,000
No, I felt the same way, Papa.

522
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:19,000
Yeah, this time you can see how strong and sure

523
00:18:19,000 --> 00:18:21,000
of herself she is.

524
00:18:21,000 --> 00:18:23,000
She's a different woman entirely from the other times.

525
00:18:23,000 --> 00:18:25,000
She's got control of her nerves now.

526
00:18:25,000 --> 00:18:28,000
Or she did have until Edmund took sick and now you can feel

527
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:31,000
her growing tense and frightened underneath.

528
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:33,000
I wish to God we could keep the truth from her but we

529
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:35,000
can't if he has to be sent to a sanatorium.

530
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:39,000
And what makes matters worse, her father died of

531
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:40,000
consumption.

532
00:18:40,000 --> 00:18:41,000
She worshipped him.

533
00:18:41,000 --> 00:18:44,000
She's never forgotten it.

534
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:45,000
It'll be hard for her.

535
00:18:45,000 --> 00:18:45,000
But she can do it.

536
00:18:45,000 --> 00:18:47,000
She's got the willpower now.

537
00:18:47,000 --> 00:18:50,000
And we must help her, Jamie, in every way we can.

538
00:18:50,000 --> 00:18:53,000
Of course, Papa.

539
00:18:53,000 --> 00:18:56,000
Outside of nerves, she seems perfectly fine this morning.

