00:19:57,000 --> 00:20:00,000
And every night since Edmund's been sick, she's been up and

573
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:03,000
down going to his room to see how he was.

574
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:06,000
Yes, that's right.

575
00:20:06,000 --> 00:20:08,000
She did stop outside his door to listen.

576
00:20:08,000 --> 00:20:12,000
It was her being in the spare room that scared me.

577
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:14,000
I couldn't help remembering that whenever she starts

578
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:16,000
sleeping alone in there, it's always been a sign it's--

579
00:20:16,000 --> 00:20:17,000
Not this time.

580
00:20:17,000 --> 00:20:18,000
It's easily explained.

581
00:20:18,000 --> 00:20:21,000
Where else could she go to get away from my snoring?

582
00:20:21,000 --> 00:20:23,000
Good God, how you could live with a mind that sees the

583
00:20:23,000 --> 00:20:25,000
worst motives behind everything is beyond me.

584
00:20:25,000 --> 00:20:27,000
Don't pull that.

585
00:20:27,000 --> 00:20:31,000
I just said I was all wrong, didn't I?

586
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:33,000
Don't you think I'm as glad of that as you are?

587
00:20:33,000 --> 00:20:34,000
I'm sure you are, Jamie.

588
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:38,000
Oh God, it would be like a curse she can't escape if

589
00:20:38,000 --> 00:20:40,000
worry over Edmund's sickness--

590
00:20:40,000 --> 00:20:42,000
it was during her long illness after bringing him into the

591
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:43,000
world that she first started the--

592
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:44,000
Oh, she didn't have anything to do with it.

593
00:20:44,000 --> 00:20:45,000
Yeah, well, I'm not blaming her.

594
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:46,000
Well, then who are you blaming?

595
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:48,000
Edmund for being born?

596
00:20:48,000 --> 00:20:49,000
Don't be a damned fool.

597
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:50,000
No one was to blame.

598
00:20:50,000 --> 00:20:51,000
The bastard of a doctor was.

599
00:20:51,000 --> 00:20:53,000
From what Mama said, he was another

600
00:20:53,000 --> 00:20:53,000
cheap quack like Hardy.

601
00:20:53,000 --> 00:20:54,000
You wouldn't pay--

602
00:20:54,000 --> 00:20:54,000
So I'm to blame.

603
00:20:54,000 --> 00:20:56,000
That's what you're driving at.

604
00:20:56,000 --> 00:20:57,000
Sh.

605
00:20:57,000 --> 00:20:59,000
We'll, if we're going to go cut that front hedge today

606
00:20:59,000 --> 00:20:59,000
we'd better get started.

607
00:20:59,000 --> 00:21:00,000
Yeah.

608
00:21:00,000 --> 00:21:03,000
It's too nice a day to waste indoors arguing.

609
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:04,000
Take a look out the window, Mary.

610
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:06,000
There's no fog in the harbor.

611
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:08,000
I'm sure the spell we've had of it is over now.

612
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:09,000
I hope so, dear.

613
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:12,000
What were you two arguing about?

614
00:21:12,000 --> 00:21:13,000
Same old stuff.

615
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:16,000
I heard you say something about a doctor.

616
00:21:16,000 --> 00:21:17,000
Oh that.

617
00:21:17,000 --> 00:21:20,000
I was saying again that Dr. Hardy is not my idea of the

618
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:24,000
world's greatest physician.

619
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:25,000
No, I wouldn't say he was either.

620
00:21:25,000 --> 00:21:26,000
That Bridget--

621
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:28,000
I thought I'd never get away.

622
00:21:28,000 --> 00:21:30,000
She told me all about her second cousin on the police

623
00:21:30,000 --> 00:21:32,000
force in St. Louis.

624
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:34,000
Well, if you're going to work on the hedge,

625
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:35,000
why don't you go?

626
00:21:35,000 --> 00:21:38,000
I mean, take advantage of the sunshine before

627
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:39,000
the fog comes back.

628
00:21:39,000 --> 00:21:42,000
Because I know it will.

629
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:45,000
I should say, the rheumatism in my hands knows.

630
00:21:45,000 --> 00:21:49,000
It's a better weather prophet than you are, James.

631
00:21:49,000 --> 00:21:50,000
How ugly they are.

632
00:21:50,000 --> 00:21:53,000
Who'd ever believe they were once beautiful.

633
00:21:53,000 --> 00:21:56,000
Now, now now now, Mary.

634
00:21:56,000 --> 00:21:58,000
They are the sweetest hands in the world.

635
00:21:58,000 --> 00:22:04,000


636
00:22:04,000 --> 00:22:06,000
Come on, Jamie, your mother's right to scold us.

