00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:17,000
I was just going upstairs to look for you.

651
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:19,000
I waited until they went out.

652
00:23:19,000 --> 00:23:21,000
I don't want to mix up in any arguments.

653
00:23:21,000 --> 00:23:22,000
I feel too rotten.

654
00:23:22,000 --> 00:23:25,000
I'm sure you don't feel half as badly as you make out.

655
00:23:25,000 --> 00:23:26,000
You're such a baby.

656
00:23:26,000 --> 00:23:30,000
You like to get us worried so we make a fuss over you.

657
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:32,000
I'm only teasing, dear.

658
00:23:32,000 --> 00:23:35,000
I know how miserably uncomfortable you must be.

659
00:23:35,000 --> 00:23:38,000
You feel better today, don't you?

660
00:23:38,000 --> 00:23:40,000
All the same, you've grown much too thin.

661
00:23:40,000 --> 00:23:43,000
You need to rest all you can.

662
00:23:43,000 --> 00:23:45,000
Here, sit down.

663
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:47,000
I'll make you comfortable.

664
00:23:47,000 --> 00:23:51,000
There, there.

665
00:23:51,000 --> 00:23:53,000
How's that?

666
00:23:53,000 --> 00:23:55,000
It's grand.

667
00:23:55,000 --> 00:23:57,000
Thanks, Mama.

668
00:23:57,000 --> 00:24:00,000
All you need is your mother to nurse you.

669
00:24:00,000 --> 00:24:02,000
Big as you are, you're still the baby of the

670
00:24:02,000 --> 00:24:03,000
family to me, you know.

671
00:24:03,000 --> 00:24:04,000
You never mind me.

672
00:24:04,000 --> 00:24:08,000
You take care of yourself, that's all that counts.

673
00:24:08,000 --> 00:24:09,000
I am, dear.

674
00:24:09,000 --> 00:24:12,000
Don't you see how fat I've grown?

675
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:15,000
Now I have to have all my dresses let out.

676
00:24:15,000 --> 00:24:24,000


677
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:26,000
They started clipping the hedge.

678
00:24:26,000 --> 00:24:30,000
Poor Jamie, how he hates working in front where

679
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:31,000
everyone passing can see him.

680
00:24:31,000 --> 00:24:35,000


681
00:24:35,000 --> 00:24:41,000
There go the Chatfields in their new Mercedes It's a

682
00:24:41,000 --> 00:24:42,000
beautiful car, isn't it?

683
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:46,000
Not like our secondhand Packard.

684
00:24:46,000 --> 00:24:51,000
Poor Jamie, he bent almost under the hedge so they

685
00:24:51,000 --> 00:24:56,000
wouldn't notice the, They bowed to your father.

686
00:24:56,000 --> 00:25:02,000
And he bowed back as if he were taking a curtain call.

687
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:04,000
In that filthy old suit I've tried to make him throw away.

688
00:25:04,000 --> 00:25:07,000
He really ought to have more pride than to make such a show

689
00:25:07,000 --> 00:25:08,000
of himself.

690
00:25:08,000 --> 00:25:11,000
He's right not to give a damn what everyone thinks.

691
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:13,000
And for Pete's sake, who has ever heard of the Chatfields

692
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:16,000
outside of this hick burg?

693
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:18,000
No one.

694
00:25:18,000 --> 00:25:20,000
You're quite right, Edmund.

695
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:22,000
Big frogs in a small puddle.

696
00:25:22,000 --> 00:25:24,000
It is stupid of Jamie.

697
00:25:24,000 --> 00:25:28,000


698
00:25:28,000 --> 00:25:35,000
Still, the Chatfields, people like them stand for something.

699
00:25:35,000 --> 00:25:40,000
I mean they have decent, presentable homes they don't

700
00:25:40,000 --> 00:25:41,000
have to be ashamed of.

701
00:25:41,000 --> 00:25:43,000
They have friends who entertain them

702
00:25:43,000 --> 00:25:45,000
and whom they entertain.

703
00:25:45,000 --> 00:25:48,000
They're not cut off from everyone.

704
00:25:48,000 --> 00:25:51,000
Not that I want anything to do with them.

705
00:25:51,000 --> 00:25:54,000
I've always hated this town and everyone in

706
00:25:54,000 --> 00:25:54,000
it, you know that.

707
00:25:54,000 --> 00:25:57,000
I never wanted to live here in the first place, but your

708
00:25:57,000 --> 00:25:59,000
father liked it.

709
00:25:59,000 --> 00:26:03,000
He insisted on building this house and I've had to come

710
00:26:03,000 --> 00:26:04,000
here every summer.

711
00:26:04,000 --> 00:26:06,000
Well this town's not so bad.

712
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:09,000
I like it well enough.

713
00:26:09,000 --> 00:26:12,000
I suppose because it's the only home we've ever had.

714
00:26:12,000 --> 00:26:13,000
I never felt it was my home.

715
00:26:13,000 --> 00:26:15,000
It was wrong from the start.

716
00:26:15,000 --> 00:26:18,000
Everything was done in the cheapest way.

717
00:26:18,000 --> 00:26:20,000
But your father would never spend the

718
00:26:20,000 --> 00:26:23,000
money to make it right.

719
00:26:23,000 --> 00:26:25,000
It's just as well we haven't any friends here, I'd be

720
00:26:25,000 --> 00:26:28,000
ashamed to have them step in the door.

721
00:26:28,000 --> 00:26:30,000
But he's never wanted family friends.

722
00:26:30,000 --> 00:26:34,000
All he likes is to hobnob with men at the

723
00:26:34,000 --> 00:26:36,000
club or in a bar room.

724
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:39,000
You've never had a chance to meet decent people here.

725
00:26:39,000 --> 00:26:41,000
I know you both would have been so different if you'd

726
00:26:41,000 --> 00:26:45,000
been able to associate with nice girls instead--

727
00:26:45,000 --> 00:26:47,000
you'd never have disgraced yourselves the way you have so

728
00:26:47,000 --> 00:26:49,000
that now no respectable parents will let their

729
00:26:49,000 --> 00:26:50,000
daughters be seen with you.

730
00:26:50,000 --> 00:26:51,000
Forget it, Mama.

731
00:26:51,000 --> 00:26:52,000
Who cares?

732
00:26:52,000 --> 00:26:55,000
Jamie and I would be bored stiff.

733
00:26:55,000 --> 00:26:57,000
And about the old man, what's the use of talking?

734
00:26:57,000 --> 00:26:58,000
You can't change him.

735
00:26:58,000 --> 00:27:00,000
Don't call your father the old man.

736
00:27:00,000 --> 00:27:01,000
You should have more respect.

737
00:27:01,000 --> 00:27:05,000


738
00:27:05,000 --> 00:27:07,000
It's useless to talk.

739
00:27:07,000 --> 00:27:09,000
But sometimes I feel so lonely.

740
00:27:09,000 --> 00:27:15,000


741
00:27:15,000 --> 00:27:17,000
Anyway Mama, you've got to be fair.

742
00:27:17,000 --> 00:27:21,000
It may have been all his fault in the beginning, but you know

743
00:27:21,000 --> 00:27:22,000
that later on, even if you'd wanted to, we couldn't have

744
00:27:22,000 --> 00:27:24,000
had people here.

745
00:27:24,000 --> 00:27:27,000


746
00:27:27,000 --> 00:27:28,000
I mean, you wouldn't have wanted--

747
00:27:28,000 --> 00:27:29,000
Don't.

748
00:27:29,000 --> 00:27:32,000
I can't bear having you remind me.

749
00:27:32,000 --> 00:27:33,000
Don't take it that way, Mama.

750
00:27:33,000 --> 00:27:34,000
Please.

751
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:40,000
I'm trying to help you because it's bad for you to forget.

752
00:27:40,000 --> 00:27:43,000
God Mama, you know I hate to remind you.

753
00:27:43,000 --> 00:27:46,000
I'm only doing it because it's been so wonderful having you

754
00:27:46,000 --> 00:27:47,000
home here the way you've been.

755
00:27:47,000 --> 00:27:48,000
And it would be terrible--

756
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:53,000
Please dear, I know you mean it for the best. I don't

757
00:27:53,000 --> 00:27:55,000
understand why you should suddenly say such things.

758
00:27:55,000 --> 00:27:58,000
What put it in your mind this morning?

759
00:27:58,000 --> 00:28:00,000
Nothing.

760
00:28:00,000 --> 00:28:02,000
Just because I feel rotten and blue, I suppose.

761
00:28:02,000 --> 00:28:03,000
Tell me the truth.

762
00:28:03,000 --> 00:28:05,000
Why are you so suspicious all of a sudden?

763
00:28:05,000 --> 00:28:05,000
I'm not.

764
00:28:05,000 --> 00:28:06,000
Oh, yes you are.

765
00:28:06,000 --> 00:28:08,000
I can feel it.

766
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:12,000
Your father and Jamie too, particularly Jamie.

767
00:28:12,000 --> 00:28:15,000
Don't start imagining things, Mama.

768
00:28:15,000 --> 00:28:18,000
It makes it so much harder, this atmosphere of constant

769
00:28:18,000 --> 00:28:21,000
suspicion, knowing everyone is spying on me, none of you

770
00:28:21,000 --> 00:28:23,000
believe in me or trust me--

771
00:28:23,000 --> 00:28:24,000
That's crazy, Mama.

772
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:24,000
We do trust you.

773
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:27,000
If there was only some place I could go to get away for a day

774
00:28:27,000 --> 00:28:31,000
or even an afternoon, some woman friend I could talk to--

775
00:28:31,000 --> 00:28:34,000
not about anything serious, simply laugh and gossip and

776
00:28:34,000 --> 00:28:35,000
forget for a while--

777
00:28:35,000 --> 00:28:39,000
someone besides the servants and stupid Cathleen--

778
00:28:39,000 --> 00:28:40,000
Stop it, Mama.

779
00:28:40,000 --> 00:28:42,000
You're getting yourself worked up all over nothing.

780
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:45,000
Because you're afraid to trust me alone.

781
00:28:45,000 --> 00:28:48,000
I insist you tell me why you act so differently this

782
00:28:48,000 --> 00:28:50,000
morning, why you felt you had to remind me.

783
00:28:50,000 --> 00:28:53,000


784
00:28:53,000 --> 00:28:56,000
It's stupid.

785
00:28:56,000 --> 00:28:58,000
It's just that I wasn't asleep when you came into my room

786
00:28:58,000 --> 00:28:59,000
last night.

787
00:28:59,000 --> 00:29:02,000
You didn't go back to your and Papa's room.

788
00:29:02,000 --> 00:29:05,000
You went into the spare room for the rest of the night.

789
00:29:05,000 --> 00:29:08,000
Because your father's snoring was driving me crazy, for

790
00:29:08,000 --> 00:29:09,000
heaven's sake.

791
00:29:09,000 --> 00:29:12,000
Haven't I often used the spare room as my bedroom?

792
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:15,000
Oh, I see what you thought.

793
00:29:15,000 --> 00:29:16,000
That was when--

794
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:16,000
I didn't think anything--

795
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:20,000
So you pretended to be asleep in order to spy on me.

796
00:29:20,000 --> 00:29:20,000
No.

797
00:29:20,000 --> 00:29:22,000
I did it because I knew if you found out I was feverish and

798
00:29:22,000 --> 00:29:24,000
couldn't sleep, it would upset you.

799
00:29:24,000 --> 00:29:27,000
Jamie was pretending to be asleep too I'm sure and, I

800
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:28,000
suppose, your father.

801
00:29:28,000 --> 00:29:28,000
Stop it, Mama.

802
00:29:28,000 --> 00:29:31,000
I can't bear, Edmund, when even you--

803
00:29:31,000 --> 00:29:33,000


804
00:29:33,000 --> 00:29:37,000
it'd serve all of you right if it was true.

805
00:29:37,000 --> 00:29:37,000
Mama don't say that--

806
00:29:37,000 --> 00:29:39,000
that's the way you talk?

807
00:29:39,000 --> 00:29:41,000
Stop suspecting me.

808
00:29:41,000 --> 00:29:43,000
Please, dear.

809
00:29:43,000 --> 00:29:46,000
You hurt me.

810
00:29:46,000 --> 00:29:52,000
I couldn't sleep because I was thinking of you.

811
00:29:52,000 --> 00:29:54,000
That's the real reason.

812
00:29:54,000 --> 00:29:57,000
I've been so worried ever since you've been sick.

813
00:29:57,000 --> 00:30:00,000


814
00:30:00,000 --> 00:30:02,000
That's foolishness.

815
00:30:02,000 --> 00:30:04,000
You know it's only a bad cold.

816
00:30:04,000 --> 00:30:06,000
Yes, of course I know that.

817
00:30:06,000 --> 00:30:09,000
Even if it should turn out to be something worse, you know

818
00:30:09,000 --> 00:30:11,000
I'll soon be all right again anyway.

819
00:30:11,000 --> 00:30:13,000
You won't worry yourself sick and you'll keep on taking care

820
00:30:13,000 --> 00:30:14,000
of yourself--

821
00:30:14,000 --> 00:30:15,000
I won't listen when you're so silly.

822
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:16,000
Of course I promise you.

823
00:30:16,000 --> 00:30:20,000
I give you my sacred word of honor.

824
00:30:20,000 --> 00:30:22,000
I suppose you're remembering I've promise before

825
00:30:22,000 --> 00:30:23,000
on my word of honor.

826
00:30:23,000 --> 00:30:24,000
No.

827
00:30:24,000 --> 00:30:25,000
I'm not blaming you, dear.

828
00:30:25,000 --> 00:30:27,000
How can you help it?

829
00:30:27,000 --> 00:30:28,000
How can any one of us forget?

830
00:30:28,000 --> 00:30:30,000
That's what makes it so hard for all of us.

831
00:30:30,000 --> 00:30:32,000
We can't forget.

832
00:30:32,000 --> 00:30:35,000
Stop it, Mama.

833
00:30:35,000 --> 00:30:39,000
I'm all right, dear.

834
00:30:39,000 --> 00:30:43,000
Except I naturally feel tired and nervous this morning after

835
00:30:43,000 --> 00:30:43,000
such a bad night.

836
00:30:43,000 --> 00:30:47,000
I really ought to go upstairs and lie down until lunch time

837
00:30:47,000 --> 00:30:47,000
and take a nap.

838
00:30:47,000 --> 00:30:48,000
What are you going to do?

839
00:30:48,000 --> 00:30:49,000
Read here?

840
00:30:49,000 --> 00:30:52,000
It would be much better for you to go out in the fresh air

841
00:30:52,000 --> 00:30:53,000
and sunshine.

842
00:30:53,000 --> 00:30:55,000
But don't get overheated, remember.

843
00:30:55,000 --> 00:30:57,000
Be sure and wear a hat.

844
00:30:57,000 --> 00:31:01,000
Or are you afraid to trust me alone?

845
00:31:01,000 --> 00:31:02,000
No.

846
00:31:02,000 --> 00:31:05,000
Can't you stop talking like that?

847
00:31:05,000 --> 00:31:10,000
No, I think you ought to take a nap.

848
00:31:10,000 --> 00:31:13,000
I'll go down and help Jamie bear up.

849
00:31:13,000 --> 00:31:15,000
I love to lie in the shade and watch him work.



